latestIgtvVideos.title: open letter to my best friend (s)
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
hello both of you 
one of you is my sister who is my best friend (@ambujanaik) and the other is my best friend who is my sister (@shikhashinde). 

aren’t i blessed? 
yes. and no. 

the journey hasn’t been all that simple. we’ve had our ups and downs, highs and lows, but we managed to stick by through it all. we fought but we came around, we loved and we loved hard. we gave it our all and that’s how we are here and here forever. 

i love you both so much that I FALL SHORT OF WORDS. ME. YES. that can happen. 

this is the three of us dancing at @shikhashinde’s sangeet - that was one of the best days of our lives. that entire week/month was the absolute best day of my life for sure. nothing else can compete with it. 

Shikha, thank you for giving us @iamtakshi my goddaughter. 
Ambuja, thank you for teaching me how to stand my ground, be badass, you strongass fiercest chotta bomb. 

thank you for existing. thank you for being. thank you for everything. 

can’t promise it’ll always be sunshine’s and daisies because eventually the night falls and the flower withers away but it regrows right back and that is just how it will be. 
i promise you both to hold your hands and never let go. 

i love you both to the moon and to saturn and then some more. 

me.

latestIgtvVideos.caption:
READ CAPTION - CHALLENGE FOR A CAUSE 

“har pal yahan jee bhar jiyo 
jo hai sama, kal ho na ho”

true. isn’t it? 
how times are changing. 
covid is taking the world at large, and reminding us everyday that we can’t take life for granted. 
every day we pray for some good news but instead 2020 just plays us further, while the cases only and only increase. 

so here we are, trying to lighten the mood & focusing on bringing forth the importance for getting a centralized online database for hospitals. so as you either sing/perform/use it in the background/use the clip of a song (you basically just have to post a video with a song - it could be anything from you singing to it playing in the background while you draw or do makeup or anything) and pass this challenge on (created by me, @madhavi.ganapathi @passionsutra and @ranalvimasooma ) we urge you to pls sign @mishikasingh’s petition (link in bio) 

i challenge @ambujanaik @meruvashisht @that_desi_feminist @goldandglittr @raashi._.smh @shreya_vermma @shikhashinde @mazelvyas_official @foodiepreneur @iakshaydogra @aishwarya.ojha @justasuburbanboy @aksharaa.haasan @shruti.sabharwal @anushaapechild @karansingharoraofficial @aarzoorshah 
to take this #covidantakshari on and sing a song from my last word - “ho” or the alphabet “o” (whatever you’re good with) and you can sing whatever language you’re comfortable in - hindi or english - and pass this on further to at least 5 other people. 
keep this antakshari going so that we can spread awareness about this campaign and get the govt to take notice!!

happy birthday to my baby bro ♥️ 
not by blood, but by heart. by chaos. by comfort.
by how you just get me without me having to explain.

you’ve been more of a brother to me than anyone ever has.
the kind that checks in. stands up. shows up.
the kind that argues with me like a brat but loves me like home.

i don’t know how or when you became this person who we can always fall back on, who’ll always and forever have our back, no matter what, who we trust with our eyes closed,
but i thank the universe every day that you did. ♥️🧿

you’re my safe space, my punching bag, my forever little baby. i love you more than i say (and definitely more than i show when i’m pulling your leg.)

i hope today wraps you up in all the love and respect you so easily give to everyone else.
because you deserve that. and so much more.

happy birthday, my baby. always in your corner. always on your team.

[Birthday Boy, Happy Birthday, Baby Bro, Love, Siblings, Chosen Family]

latestPosts.caption:
a year can change everything.
the silence that used to hurt,
the ache, the noise, the sting; everything that once broke me apart,
now sounds a lot like peace.

i stopped searching for the why,
for the apology, the clean goodbye.
some endings don’t need a final word—
just distance, and time,
and truth finally heard.

i kept waiting for the sorry,
for the shift, the second chance,
but by the time he knelt down,
head in his hands,
it was too late to dance that dance.

i had cried all the tears.
grieved the could-have-beens.
mourned the version of love
that only i believed in.

so no, i didn’t need his words.
not anymore.
because peace came quietly
when i closed that door.

hope the highs
were worth the fall.
because i rose from it—
stronger than it all.

- tejaswini divya naik

#happymothersday to
my mother and my grandmother —
women who lived through war
but never let it reach their children’s eyes.
who carried the weight of worry alone
so we wouldn’t have to.
who kept the fear folded deep into silence
and still lit the diya every evening
as if the world outside wasn’t falling apart.

they taught me
that it’s never wrong
to demand my right.

that beauty isn’t measured
by the false standards of society —
it’s measured by what a person is made of,
and how they treat others.

that standing up
and raising my voice
doesn’t make me lesser of a girl.
that fighting, brick by brick,
only makes you stronger.

because you don’t have to gulp cruelty
like a forced medicine down your throat.
you’re not chained to white sheets,
and this is not a hospital bed.
and calling a criminal a criminal
doesn’t make you a victim.

stare down
those hawk eyes.
stand in the face of injustice,
and fight the devil —

because my mother taught me
that it’s never wrong
to fight for my right,
and stand up for what i believe in.

and maybe that’s where I get it from —
this fire that doesn’t ask for permission.
this strength that feels inherited,
carried forward
like stories we weren’t told,
but somehow always knew.

[Mother, Grandmother, Mother’s day, Love, Strength]

Review of Smokes and Whiskey & One for Sorrow

Reading Tejaswini’s poetry is like flipping through your own diary—only she writes the things you didn’t know how to say.
Smokes and Whiskey tastes like a love you romanticized too long, like lipstick on coffee mugs and memories that linger. Her lines feel like late-night confessions, like: “Some people are storms. I was the matchstick.”
It’s not just heartbreak—it’s the poetry of surviving it.

One for Sorrow is softer, like exhaling. It’s healing stitched into verses, sorrow that teaches you how to bloom anyway. A reminder that even the quietest ache has a melody. “I became my own safe place,” she writes—and you believe her.

Together, these books feel like walking through your past barefoot and brave. For anyone who’s loved, lost, and found themselves in the wreckage—this is for you.
It doesn’t just hurt. It sings.
